  <section class="section">
    <h2>Most Poker Players Think About Hands. Winners Think About Decisions.</h2>

```
<p>
  Most players judge poker by the hand they just won or lost. They remember the bad beat. They remember the bluff that worked. They remember the big pot that slipped away.
</p>

<p>
  But poker is not really won one hand at a time. Poker is won by making better decisions again and again at the key checkpoints that appear throughout a session, a tournament, a cash game, or an entire poker career.
</p>

<p>
  Checkpoint Poker: The Core System gives you a simple way to evaluate those decisions.
</p>

<div class="highlight">
  A plus-one decision moves you closer to winning. A minus-one decision moves you farther away.
</div>

<p>
  That idea sounds simple because it is supposed to be simple. Poker gets confusing when players chase emotion, ego, revenge, fear, or short-term results. The Checkpoint Poker system brings the game back to the decision in front of you.
</p>
```

  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <h2>The Problem With Random Poker Advice</h2>

```
<p>
  Poker players collect tips. They watch videos. They memorize charts. They study hands. They hear advice about position, aggression, pot odds, ranges, blockers, pressure, bankrolls, and table selection.
</p>

<p>
  The problem is not that the advice is useless. The problem is that most players never turn it into a working system.
</p>

<p>
  When the pressure rises, scattered advice disappears. A player who thought he understood poker suddenly starts guessing. He calls because he is frustrated. He bluffs because he wants respect. He folds because he is scared. He chases because he wants to get even.
</p>

<p>
  Checkpoint Poker is designed to stop that.
</p>

<p>
  Instead of asking, “Do I feel like playing this hand?” the system trains you to ask better questions.
</p>

<ul>
  <li>Does this decision improve my position?</li>
  <li>Does this decision expose me to unnecessary damage?</li>
  <li>Am I reacting emotionally or thinking clearly?</li>
  <li>Am I creating pressure or absorbing pressure?</li>
  <li>Is this a plus-one decision or a minus-one decision?</li>
</ul>
```

